                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="448613" author="JIRAUSER19288" created="Tue, 18 Mar 2025 11:47:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I think the seq_file limit is its &quot;size&quot; field. &quot;seq_printf&quot; may return -1 in case &quot;count&quot; (the printed information) is larger than the &quot;size&quot; of the seq_file (see &lt;a href=&quot;https://elixir.bootlin.com/linux/v6.13.7/source/fs/seq_file.c#L386&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;). &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I believe this ticket may have come up from the way nids are printed. In this case, there is indeed a check in its &quot;seq_show&quot; to not overflow the seq_file&apos;s size field, see in this &lt;a href=&quot;https://review.whamcloud.com/c/fs/lustre-release/+/8036/19/lustre/mdt/mdt_lproc.c#672&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;function of the patch&lt;/a&gt;. Nevertheless, this does not use seq_printf() to print the same way nodemap functions do. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I have also run a few tests with a large output (&amp;gt; 1.4 million characters) from the same seq_show function. Depending on the amount printed, the seq_file&apos;s size field grows dynamically (doubling each time, starting from 4096 bytes and, in this test case, 2 MiB). I&apos;m not sure if there is a limit before running out of memory, but given these observations and if this is enough headroom, this may not be an issue.&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="448595" author="sebastien" created="Tue, 18 Mar 2025 09:28:23 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;As far as I can see, there were no changes in nodemap_lproc.c in this direction since 2015, and seq_show is still in use to dump nodemap information. Although I am not sure what the seq_file limit is, it seems the seq_file interface reads data in chunks defined by the page size. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Among all the nodemap properties, only id mappings and NID ranges can be very large, the other properties being single values or paths limited to PATH_MAX.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In my testing, I managed to add more than 1 million id mappings, and more than 1 million NID ranges to a nodemap. Then I was able to dump the corresponding values, without being limited or truncated.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So I was not able to hit any limitation in that area.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="448566" author="adilger" created="Tue, 18 Mar 2025 07:21:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=sebastien&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;sebastien&quot;&gt;sebastien&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=mvef&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;mvef&quot;&gt;mvef&lt;/a&gt;, is this still an issue, or has this been fixed already?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
